Wow, this has been going on a long time, and still I see people dancing around one of the easiest things you can do. Assume the rest of the gridview/repeater/whatever has been created around the following snippet.
<br />
<br />&lt;ItemTemplate&gt; 
<br /> &lt;asp:LinkButton runat="server" 
<br /> ID="lbIsActive" 
<br /> OnCommand="MethodName"
<br /> CommandArgument='&lt;%# Eval("SomeIDOrValue") %&gt;' &gt;Text or img&lt;/asp:LinkButton&gt;
<br />&lt;/ItemTemplate&gt;
<br />-----
<br />protected void MethodName(object sender, CommandEventArgs e)
<br />{
<br /> int id = Convert.ToInt32(e.CommandArgument);
<br /> //Do work here...
<br />}
<br />
<br />NOWHERE in there does it say you have to use a row command. The event will be wired up directly from the linkbutton to the codebehind. 
<br />
<br />If you need to capture the row, then put the CommandName = "Select" or "Edit" and wire up those events for the gridview... or you can resort to the good old rowcommand.

